{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_queenofspades_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280608737/1958031601/0025.xml":{"full_text":"The Recession: Search for a Quick Cure\nEarly last June the Joint Economic Committee of Congress\nrounded up 33 economists representing all the major schools of\nthought and asked their opinion oh the state of the economy.\nThe 33 were virtually unanimous in their opinion that all was\ngoing well, and that the only possible cause for concern was the\ncontinuing inflationary trend.\nBut by late summer many of those same economists were be-\nginning to see the first symptoms\nof a recession.\nOne of the things that troubled\nthem was a persistent stability in\nfigures on industrial production at\na time when the figures should\nhave been moving forward. This\nleveling off, due in part to peak\ninventories, was occurring despite\nthe fact that production capacity\nwas being increased by. a confident\nbusiness community. The econo\nmists feared that unless inven\ntories could be reduced' and pro\nduction gains resumed, 'many in\ndustrial facilities would soon be\nidle. which would mean, of\ncourse, idle workers also.\nThere were other danger signs,\ntoo: The *ito market had beef!\nslower tha. expected all summer,\nand there was little reason to hope\nfor a strong recovery. Our net for\neign investment position showed a\ndistressing weakening. There had\nbeen a sharp drop in world-wide\ncommodity prices.\nIt wasn\u2019t long before leading\neconomists, both in and out of\nGovernment, were suggesting that\nUncle Sam had better take some\naction to forestall possible trouble\nin the winter. One of these was\nArthur Burns, former chairman of\nthe President\u2019s Council of Eco\nnomic Advisers, who thought that\nthe Federal Reserve Board ought\nto consider looser credit.\nBut economic statistics just can\u2019t\nkeep up with the facts, and the\nstatistics the board thought it\nneeded to justify looser credit were\nnot in. For instance, as late as\nNovember the Government still\ndid not have the figures on cor\nporate profits for the third quarter\nof 1957, which would have given\nsome insight into future business\nexpansion or contraction.\nDespite the misgivings, as sum\nmer ended it was not hard for\nmany economists to stick to their\nposition that the big problem still\nwas inflation. And certainly the\nconsumer, facing steadily increas\ning costs of living, would have\nagreed. It was at about that time\nthat the Federal Government took\ntwo courses which many observers\nhave since claimed were harmful:\nThe Federal Reserve Board, ap\nparently convinced that the real\ndanger was inflation, further tight\nened up on money. And the ad\nministration, under pressure from\nboth parties in Congress to keep a\nbalanced budget, ordered cutbacks\nin planned spending for civil and\nmilitary projects.\nBy December, the \u201cleveling off\u2019\u2019\nhad become an admitted recession.\nIndustrial production as a whole\nwas still dropping, and steel and\nautos\u2014two vital segments of the\neconomy\u2014were especially hard hit.\nPersonal income was moving\ndownward, unemployment was up\nsharply and the number of average\nhours worked in manufacturing\nwas falling rapidly.\nThe blame has been widely dis\ntributed. Overexpansion by busi\nness as a result of overconfidence\nhas been given as one reason.\nWage demands of labor unions\nhave been blamed. Some say that\nmoney was held tight too long.\nOthers, particularly in labor\u2019s\nranks, say the culprit was an ad\nministration policy that encour\naged business investment while\ndiscouraging expansion of con\nsumer buying power.\nWhere We Stand\nBy last week, however, there\nwas less effort to fix blame and\nmore effort to find a solution\u2014\nand soon.\nThe pressure for action, with its\nincreasing pote of urgency, was\nbuilding up with these facts as\na background:\nUnemployment, numbering 5.2\nmillion workers, was at a 19-year\npeak.\nLatest figures showed February\nto be the slowest month for hous\ning starts in nine years.\nIndustrial production was down\nin February for the sixth straight\nmonth.\nBusiness failures were at the\nhighest level since World War 11.\nA Federal Reserve Board sur\nvey showed that the number of\npersons planning to buy new homes\nand cars in 1956 had dropped sub\nstantially. Also, the board said,\nindustry spending for plants and\nequipment this year will be off\n13 per cent from last year.\nRail freight loadings were\ndown 19.1 per cent from the same\ntime last year.\nThe steel Industry was operat\ning at barely 50 per cent of its\ncapacity.\nThe search for away out was\nshaping up as a. major political\nissue to be taken to the hustings\nin this fall\u2019s elections.\nThe political jockeying was over\ntax reduction vs. public works.\nBoth parties want credit for pro\nviding the cure, but neither wants\nto be saddled with the blame for\na hasty action that could bring\na new spiral of inflation.\nDecision Deferred\nPresident Elsenhower, for the\ntime being at least, is standing by\nhis position against a tax reduc\ntion. He met for two and a half\nhours with his cabinet on Friday\nand the decision was to defer any\ntax cut proposals until the figures\nare in on the economy's March\nperformance. The administration\nhas been depending on a healthy\nseasonal upturn in employment\nthis month to Justify its position.\nIt has been reported, however,\nthat if March statistics\u2014due in\nBusiness\nGeneral News\nmid-April\u2014are not as <icourag\ning as expected, then the adminis\ntration will put a tax cut plan,\nnow ready, before Congress.\nMr. Eisenhower has good reason\nto be cautious about cutting taxes,\nsince he bears the responsibility\nfor keeping the budget in balance.\nA tax reduction sufficiently large\nto halt the recession would also\nbe large enough\u2014along with the\nother adversities a balanced\nbudget faces to put the 1959\nbudget perhaps as much as $lO\nbillion in the red. Also. Mr. Eisen\nhower equated a balanced budget\nwith \u201cfiscal integrity\u201d in his elec\ntion campaigns.\nThe administration in recent\nweeks has accepted the need for\na step-up in spending for mili\ntary and civilian projects, and\n$386 million of the latter which\nwere shelved by last year\u2019s econ\nomy drive have been reactivated.\nMr. Eisenhower also wants an\namendment to the Highway Act\nthat will apportion $2.2 billion\nmore of Federal funds to the\nStates. Democrats, however, can\nclaim credit for first suggesting\nthese actions.\nBut arguments for immediate\ntax reductions persist. Some\nDemocrats\u2014not the party\u2019s lead\nership in Congress, but enough\nto establish a record for their\nparty\u2014are betting that expanded\npublic works projects won\u2019t be\nenough to halt the recession. They\nclaim further that this step takes\ntoo long. They are supported by\nthe AFL-CIO, leaders\nspent much of last week trying\nto convince the administration to\nchange its position.\nDemocratic Senator Douglas,\nthe former economics professor\nfrom Illinois, tried to get the\nSenate to approve a proposal to\nreduce the rate on the first SI,OOO\nof individual taxable income and\nrepeal or reduce excise taxes. His\nplan was defeated Thursday at\na night session of the Senate.\nThe vote was 71 to 14\u201412 of the\n14 being Democrats.\nBut the dozen Democrats who\nvoted for the Douglas plan do\nnot necessarily represent the\nwhole body of Senate Democratic\nopinion favoring a tax cut. Sen\nator Douglas tried to tact his\nproposal in amendment form onto\na Mouse bill dealing with insur\nance company taxes.\nVirginia\u2019s Senator Byrd, who\nhimself opposes a tax cut now. may\nhave expressed the opinion of\nmany Democrats who felt tax re\nduction is necessary now when\nhe argued that the Douglas pro\nposal seemed \u201cvery unwise.\u201d\n\"We should all recognize the\nfact that tax measures must\noriginate in the House of Repre\nsentatives,\u201d the Virginian said. \u201cI\nhave a feeling that the Commit\ntee on Ways and Means of the\nHouse will resent the action\nThe theory behind the tax cut\ncure is that it is a quick way to\nput more money into the hands\nof consumers, thereby setting off\na chain reaction of increased buy\ning. reduced inventories and re\nnewed demand for the manu\nfactured goods to be made by\nworkers now unemployed.\nIn the two most recent re\ncessions\u2014in 1949 and 1954\u2014tax\nrelief was given early. The 1949\nreduction (over President Tru\nman\u2019s veto) was credited with in\ncreasing the gross national prod\nuct by s2l billion in six months.\nIn 1954 the high rates of the Ko\nrean War level were cut back at\nthe same time credit was loosened,\nand the recovery was immediate.\nIn both cases, the Treasury\u2019s tax\nrevenues increased, despite the\nlower rates, because of the im-\nLEGISLATION DOUBTFUL\nKohler Strike Hearings Split McClellan Committee\nBy WILLIAM HINES\nStar Stall Writer\nIf education has been correctly\ndefined as the art of emphasizing\nthe obvious, the educational func\ntion of Congress has been carried\nout admirably in the past three\nweeks by the Senate Rackets Com\nmittee.\nSo far. virtually nothing sub\nstantive has been brought out in\nthe long and often rancorous hear\nings that was not already in the\n20.000 pages of National Labor Re\nlations Board testimony on the\nKobler Co. strike. But much\nof what has been confined to that\nrecord has been put before the\npublic for the first time.\nThe end of the hearings is not\nyet in sight, and, of course, some\nthing could happen in the weeks\nahead to change the outlook. But\nit is highly doubtful at this time\nthat anything in the way of re\nmedial legislation will result.\nThe decision of Senator Ken\nnedy, Democrat of Massachusetts,\nlast week to Introduce antiracket\neering measures was a natural out\ngrowth of the committee\u2019s 1957\nhearings, in which proof of mis\ndeeds abounded. But the current\nhearings are different.\nA Different Cast\nIn the place of venal labor\nleaders are honest\u2014often pain\nfully honest\u2014ones. And in the\nplace of sail-trimming employers,\nwilling to make any kind of shabby\ndeal with a crooked unionist, are\na coterie of rugged individualists\nfflje Jhmdciij ftaf\nTHE WEEK IN PERSPECTIVE\n.rv Hi .BWiIIWIFBKrPtt mw STiAi\nI iiiiiPiFTWr m wmteu, WBmfry MS* Mpf\nI Mil gH\u00dftcfK&> \u25a0M.Mfr\nIlf t is W\n\"'.v..' 11 v :?-W y\n7 IP 11. 7 i 1 VKiPjnHF W f\n\u2022|t il\u2018 Bp|r lijr\n1 Ph\u00df y S\n<4O f w V m j mSUSMmSA m\nA r: \u2019\u2022w'\"\"'\";' mk BH\n\ni\nSORE SPOT\u2014In Detroit, hard hit by the recession, loid-off factory workers are keeping the unemployment compensation office staff busy.\nmediate improvement In business.\nActually, the contest over a tax\ncut versus public works spending\nmay be no contest at all long be\nfore November\u2019s elections. If\nthose who argue that recovery will\nbe extremely difficult are correct,\nthen it is likely that the ailing\neconomy will get a strong dose of\nboth measures.\nAction, Too\nAll was not merely argument\nat the Capitol last week. Congress\nstarted administering some pre\nliminary treatment and was pre\nparing more. These were the ma\njor steps taken:\nThe Senate unanimously passed\na $l.B billion emergency housing\nbill designed to provide jobs for a\nhalf million workers.\nBy a 3-to-l margin the House\npassed, against the President's\nwishes, a bill authorizing $1.5 bil\nlion for improving rivers and har\nbors and controlling floods.\nThe Senate, with one dissent\ning vote, passed resolutions call\ning on Mr. Eisenhower to step up\nspending on military and civil pub\nlic works projects for which funds\nalready have been appropria'ted.\n(As of December 31, there was a\nbacklog of more than $7 billion\nworth of military and civil works\nprojects on which appropriated\nmoney had not been spent.)\nHow Deep?\nJust how deep are the wounds?\nEconomists are in general agree\nment that current conditions are\nmore serious than they were in\neither of the mild recessions of\n1949 and 1954.\nBut nobody yet is ready to say\nthat the Nation is about to be\nthrown into a long full-fledged\ndepression. For one thing, most\nof the unemployment is to be\nfound in the durable goods in\ndustries\u2014autos, home appliances\nand the like. The service indus\ntries\u2014those which sell not goods,\nbut services\u2014are remaining en\ncouragingly stable, and in some\nareas even still booming. If the\nrecession spreads to this section\nof the economy, then, the experts\nwarn, we\u2019ll be in real trouble.\nAnother promisiqjg factor is\nwhat appears to be a beginning of\na decline in Inventories. In Jan\nuary inventory stocks were cut by\nS6OO million.\nWhenever it ends\u2014or by what\nwho quite frankly want nothing to\ndo with organized labor.\nIt is easy for Senators to be\nfor the Kennedy bill, just as it is\neasy for them to be against sin.\nAs Senator Ervin, Democrat of\nNorth Carolina, expressed it last\nweek, \u201cthe politician makes the\ngeneral statement, \u2018I believe in\nthe greatest good for the greatest\nnumber and I'll do what I can to\nachieve it.\u2019\u201d\nBut when it comes to remedial\nlegislation in a matter like the\nKohler strike, one departs from\nthe field of penal law and gets\ninto the arena of political con\ntroversy. Any law repressive of\nthe rights of one side or the other\nin a Kohler-type dispute, could be\ndescribed by its enemies as (1)\nsocialistic or (2) union-busting.\nThat it might be neither is quite\nbeside the point. So is the strong\npossibility that antigoon legisla\ntion\u2014directed against both sides\n\u2014might be a highly desirable ad\ndition to the statute books.\nIf it is probable that nothing of\na legislative nature will result\nfrom the UAW hearings, what\ndoes the public get tor its money?\nEntertainment, for one thing.\nWith the arrival of television on\nthe scene last week, that aspect\nof the hearings was broadened\nconsiderably.\nAnother product, it appears is\na certain amount of public educa\ntion\u2014though it is questionable\nwhether it is the kind of educa\ntion the committee would have\nwanted.\nWASHINGTON, D. C\u201e MARCH 16, 1958\nmeans it is ended\u2014the halt down\nward is expected to be gradual:\nthe longer it lasts the more\ngradual the upturn.\nThe recession, of course, is\nplaying hob with Mr. Eisenhower s\ncurrent budget. This was the\nbudget which he presented to\nCongress in January, 1957\u2014bal\nanced by an anticipated surplus\nof $l.B billion. By January, 1958,\nthis surplus had become a deficit\nof S4OO million. Now, with 3!j\nmonths of the fiscal year still\nremaining, the deficit is running\nclose to SBOO million.\nThe upcoming budget, presented\nin January and effective on July\n1, was never balanced except in\nthe dreams of Budget Bureau\nofficials. Increased spending for\nboth defense and civil benefits\ncould add several billion dollars\nto its cost in the face of dwindling\nrevenues. Added to this a tax cut\nof from $5 billion to $7 billion\nwould push the 1958-9 budget\ninto the red by aa much as $lO\nbillion or more.\nAtomic Bombs:\nFall and Blast\n\u201cThere was lots of smoke and\ndust and pine trees began to\nfall, then the roof caved in. I\ngot hit in the side twice with\nsomething.\u201d\nThis is how a \u201cvictim\u201d of the\nfirst atomic bomb dropped on\nUnited States soil described his\nexperience last week.\nWalter Gregg was repairing a\nbrtich in his garage near Florence,\nS. C. on Tuesday when a B-47\nbomber inadvertently dropped an\nunarmed nuclear bomb in his\nyard. The TNT charge in the de\nvice, which is used in some but\nnot all atomic bombs, exploded\nand dug a crater 75 feet wide\nand 35 feet deep between Mr.\nGregg\u2019s house and garage.\nThe accident touched off both\ndomestic and international reper\ncussions. In Great Britain, where\nthere is some sensitivity about\nUnited States atomic bombers\nbased there, the incident started\na debate in the House of Commons\nover the risks involved in permit\nting nuclear bombers to fly over\nBritain.\nIn Washington Defense Secre\nRightly or wrongly, the impres\nsion is abroad that the committee\nis more interested at present in\npolitics than in labor.\nFrom Prepared Positions\nThat the two sides on the com\nmittee started from well-prepared\npositions can hardly be doubted.\nThe Democrats (less Senator Mc-\nNamara of Michigan) went into\nthe hearings with an all but\navowed desire to make the small\nest possible mole hill out of the\nmountain at hand. The Republi\ncans (less Senator Ives of New\nYork) were out to get UAW Pres\nident Walter Reuther at all costs.\nSenator Ives, coming from the\nliberal East, could hardly afford\nto have himself bracketed with\nthe Ooldjvater-Curtls-Mundt axis.\nAnd Senator McNamara, if not\nexactly sympathetic to Mr. Reu\nther, was beholden to him and\ncould not afford to be as de\ntached as the other Democrats.\nFrom these starting points, the\nvarious Senators have been forced\ninto the points of view they now\nappear to hold. Senators Oold\nwater. Curtis and Mundt would\nargue heatedly \u2014and quite pos\nsibly with justification\u2014that they\nare not anti-labor. But in order\nto make Walter Reuther and all\nhis works look as bad as possible,\nthey have been forced to defend\nthe company against attacks from\nall sources.\nAnd since\u2014as even friends of\nthe Kohler Co. admit privately\u2014\nthe company looks unbelieveably\nbad in many ways, the three Re\ntary Neil H. McElroy sent his \"deep\nregrets\u201d to the six persons, includ\ning four children, who were\nslightly injured on the Gregg farm.\nAnd Representative Mendel Riv\ners, South Carolina Democrat,\nsaid: \"When they start, dropping\nbombs on South Carolina, it\u2019s\neverybody\u2019s business.\" The Stra\ntegic Air Command, whose bomber\ndropped the device, and the De\nfense Department agreed. A high\nlevel investigation was ordered.\nThe accident occurred when the\nbomb broke loose from a shackle\nin ths plane, fell through the\nbomb bay and dropped 15,000\nfeet into Mr. Gregg\u2019s yard.\nThe Defense Department as\nsured the public that there was\nno danger from radiation as a\nresult of the accident. The nu\nclear bombs, when carried or\ntraining missions, are never as\nsembled for explosion, it has been\nTHE WORLD SCENE\nThe Summit: More Soviet Pressure\nPick a goal then pursue it un\nswervingly\u2014that has long been\nstandard advice to the ambitious.\nDistractions must be shunned, by\nplays avoided lest momentum be\nlessened or the path be lost.\nNikita Khrushchev, First Secre\ntary of the Soviet Communist\nParty and effective head of the\nRussian government, has followed\nthat advice closely in his relentless\nquest for a new \u2018\u2018meeting at the\nsummit\u201d by the heads of state of\nthe major powers. Virtually every\nstatement, letter or cocktail party\ntidbit to come, from the Kremlin\nin recent months has been tied to\nthe summit proposal in some way.\nIt was clear that Moscow had\nthe summit meeting and that alone\non its mind last week when Rus\nsian leaders (1> let it be known\nthat the Soviet boycott of the U. N.\nDisarmament Commission would\ncontinue, and charged that United\nStates moves to revive the issue\nin the U.N. were transparent at\ntempts to distract world attention\nfrom the proposed summit con\nference; (2) disclosed in an official\nForeign Ministry statement Friday\nthat negotiations between East\nand West on preliminary steps\ntoward a summit conference were\nalready going on; (3) appealed\npublican conservatives frequency\nlook bad along with the concern\nthat they champion.\nSenators McClellan. Ervin and\nKennedy in the past three weeks\nhave not acted so much as re\nacted. Had they not offered only\ntoken resistance to the Goldwater-\nCurtis-Mundt onslaught, it is dif\nficult to know what kind of pic\nture of the Kohler strike might\nhave emerged.\nPot and Kettle\nThe union, in many respects,\nhas looked at least as bad as the\ncompany. In defending the union\nDemocrats have on occasion laid\nthemselves open to a charge of\nbeing sympathetic to labor mis\ndeeds.\nThis charge, of course, is no\nmore justified necessarily than the\nanti-labor tag would necessarily\nbe justified against the Republi\ncans.\nSenators McClellan and Ervin\ncan hardly be regarded as parti\nsans of Mr. Reuther. They come\nfrom \u201cright-to-work-law\" States\u2014\nArkansas and North Carolina\u2014and\nabhor the New Deal, ADA. egali\ntarian views of the UAW presi\ndent. They are, in a word, stuck\nwith him.\nSenator Kennedy is a special\ncase. He is popularly regarded\nas an aspirant for President in\n1960; therefore, he labors at the\ncommittee table under disabilities\nwhich do not affect the other\nmembers. He cannot antagonize\nso powerful a figure as Mr. Reu\nEditorials\nEditorial Features\nsaid. They contain, in addition\nto the nuclear materials, com\npartments of TNT.\nBefore an explosion can occur\nthe bomb's components must be\nassembled and a triggering device,\nalso containing TNT charges,\nmust be inserted. The trigger is\nkept by the plane's navigator and\nit, the bomb proper and several\nother devices necessary to the\nassembly, are kept widely sep\narated on the plane, each in the\ncustody* of a different crew mem\nber. The parts are assembled,\nafter a countdown, only when the\nmission is a test drop or a war\ntime drop.\nBlast Detection\nIn another atomic development,\nmeanwhile, the Atomic Energy\nCommission confirmed that an\nunderground nuclear blast in Ne-\nonce again to the West to go\n\u201chalf-way\u201d with the Soviet Union\ntoward a workable settlement of\nthe world\u2019s outstanding problems,\nand (4) formally proposed in a\nKremlin statement that interna\ntional co-operation in the peaceful\nuse of outer space under the aegis\nof the U.N. be a subject for the\nsummit talks.\nThe Soviet Union had remained\nrelatively quiet during the early\npart of the week, plainly awaiting\ndevelopments at the Manila meet\ning of member nations of the\nSoutheast Asia Treaty Organiza\ntion at Manila.\nAs the SEATO meeting came to\nan unspectacular close with issu\nance of a communique warning, as\nin previous years, of intensified\nCommunist efforts to move into\nthat area and a slap at \u201cneutral\nist\u201d nations, Secretary of State\nDulles met with his colleagues,\nFrench Foreign Minister Christian\nPineau and British Foreign Secre\ntary Selwyn Lloyd, to talk over\nthe summit question.\nAlthough the three moulders of\nforeign policy agreed publicly that\na summit meeting would be desi\nrable \u201cto take serious decisions on\nserious problems.\u201d Mr. Dulles\ncalled the Soviet stand on the\nther. but by the same token, he\ncannot give the impression of\nbeing overly sympathetic to him.\nNow the battle lines, being\ndrawn, are being defended val\niantly. The vigor that has gone\ninto their defense has given rise\nto a certain amount of tension\nhard feeling if you will\u2014within\nthe committee.\nThe result of the split into\n\u201cmajor\" and \u201cminor\" staffs is\nthat the resulting group, in the\nKohler hearings, is now operating\nnot as one committee but as two.\nThe likelihood of its ever operat\ning again as a .single bipartisan\nbody seems remote.\nThis situation is ironic because\nit grows out of Senator McClel\nlan\u2019s solution to a Democrats vs.\nRepublican deadlock.\nThe deadlock was over what to\ndo about Mr. Reuther. The Repub\nlicans insisted that his appear\nance be deferred until late in the\nhearings. The Democrats wanted\nthe union leader (and his oppo\nsite number from management.\nHerbert Kohler) to open the\nhearings with sworn statements\nand supposing evidence.\nTo crack the impasse. Senator\nMcClellan voted with the Repub- j\nllcans. Immediately afterwards\nhe told reporters he did so to\npreserve the unity and usefulness\nof the committee.\nNow three weeks after, many\nobservers are wondering whether\nthere is any unity\u2014or much use- j\nfulness\u2014left to preserve.\nvada last summer had been de\ntected on seismographic instru\nments 2,320 miles away in Alaska.\nThe confirmation took the form of\na correction of an error in an AEC\nstatement on March 6.\nThe Incident had important im\nplications in the controversy over\ndisarmament and the halting of\nnuclear bomb tests. This was its\nbackground:\nThe AEC last September ex\nploded the device deep in a cave\nin Nevada while seeking, among\nother things, a safe method of\ndetonations that would permit\ntesting devices for both military\nand civilian potentials.\nOn March 6 the AEC released\npart of its findings to the public.\nIn its statement it noted: \u201cThe\nearth waves were recorded by seis\nmological stations at Los Angeles,\nabout 250 miles, air line, from the\nshot mesa. This was the maximum\ndistance at which the shock was\nrecorded.\u201d\nIf that statement had been\ncorrect it would have been an in\ndication that, contrary to the\n:laims of many persons who want\nto end tests, nuclear tests could\nbe conducted secretly by any na\ntion regardless of any ban that\nmight exist.\nAfter the AEC\u2019s statement some\ndoubting scientists took their\ndoubts to Senator Humphrey,\nMinnesota Democrat and chair\nman of the Foreign Relations\nCommittee's Disarmament Sub\ncommittee.\nSenator Humphrey on Tuesday\nnoted that Harold Stassen, the\nPresident\u2019s former disarmament\nadviser, had told the subcommittee\nthat the blast had been recorded\non every seismic instrument in a\nthousand-mile radius. On the\nsame day the AEC deleted the\nsentence referring to the 250-mile\nmaximum detection and substi\ntuted the following in its March 6\nstatement:\n\u201cSeismological stations of the\nUnited States Coast and Geodetic\nSurvey as far away as College\n(near Fairbanks). Alaska, about\n2.320 miles from the shot mesa,\nrecorded the earth waves.\u201d\nThe backtracking, said Senator\nHumphrey, \u201cgives the impression\nthat scientific facts are being used\nby someone to prove a political\npoint.\u201d The Joint Atomic Com\nmittee in Congress, however, ab\nsolved the AEC of playing politics\nand said the error was an honest\none.\nsubject \"ridiculous,\u201d and declared\nexisting differences between East\nand West were so great as to make\nthe success of a summit confer\nence \u201cvery doubtful.\u201d\nThen, while Mr. Dulles flew on\nto Formosa to reiterate his op\nposition to recognition of Com\nmunist China and to reaffirm\ncontinued American support for\nChiang Kai-shek\u2019s Nationalist re\ngime, the Soviet Union opened up\nits new offensive on the summit\nquestion.\nIn its proposition yesterday to\naccept international co-operation\nm the neaceiul utilization of outer\nspace as a summit topic, Moscow\noffered also to accept prohibition\nof intercontinental range missiles\nif the United States concurrently\nwould liquidate the string of air\nbases now ringing Soviet territory.\nWashington as of late yesterday\nhad made no official reply to the\nlatest Soviet approach. But State\nDepartment sources indicated the\nterms were unacceptable. Also, in\na reply to the announcement that\nRussia would continue to boycott\nthe U. N. Disarmament Commis\nsion, the Department declared the\nUnited States would not be a party\nto \u201ccontinued flouting\u201d of the U. N.\non the disarmament issue. The De\npartment also said this country\nwould not talk disarmament \"at\nthe summit\u201d without a proper link\nwith the U. N\nThe SEATO Session\nThe swift plays on the summit\nchessboard served, in part at\nleast, to downgrade the SEATO\nmeeting in world importance. But\nSEATO. as an Integral part of\nMr. Dulles\u2019 own \"containment\u2019'\npolicy toward the Communist\nworld, is an important bastion of\nthe non-Communtst defenses tn\na vital area of the world.\nSEATO was formed at Manila\nin September, 1954. by eight na\ntions with interests in the South\neast Aslan area: Britain. France,\nthe United States, Australia, New\nZealand. Pakistan and the Philip\npines The pact pledged its mem\nber states \"to resist armed attack\"\nin the region and also to \"prevent\nand courier subversive activities.\"\nNationalism and anticolonialism\nkept many key nations of the area\nout of the SEATO. \u201cNeutralism\"\nwas the term applied to the reser\nvations of Indonesia, India. Cey\nlon and Burma: they wanted no\nalignment with either side in the\ncold war.\nLast week SEATO\u2019s council re\npeated the theme of previous an\nnual meetings: That the Com\nmunist threat was as great as ever,\nwith the immediate emphasis\nbeing placed on economic and\nsocial penetration rather than\nmilitary. But this year there was\na new consideration\u2014the rivalry\nbetween East and West as to\nwhich was ready to proser the\nmost economic aid to have-not\nnations.\nPakistan's Nawab Mezaffar All\nKhan Quizilbash, Minister of Com\nmerce and Industry, warned\nContinued on Page A-21\nA-25","height":"28994","width":"18360"}}
